# Type Conversion (Java) — Quick Revision Notes

Type Conversion means converting one data type into another.

---

# 1. Implicit Type Conversion (Widening)

Java automatically converts a smaller data type into a larger data type.

## Example

```java
int a = 10;
double b = a;   // int → double

System.out.println(b);
```

### Output

```text
10.0
```

### Memory Flow

```text
int (4 bytes) → double (8 bytes)
```

✅ No data loss occurs.

---

# 2. Explicit Type Conversion (Casting / Narrowing)

Java requires manual conversion when converting a larger type into a smaller type.

## Example

```java
double a = 10.75;
int b = (int) a;

System.out.println(b);
```

### Output

```text
10
```

### Memory Flow

```text
double (8 bytes) → int (4 bytes)
```

⚠ Decimal part is lost.

---

# 3. Common Type Conversion Examples

## int → long

```java
int a = 100;
long b = a;
```

---

## int → double

```java
int a = 50;
double b = a;
```

---

## double → int

```java
double a = 25.99;
int b = (int) a;

System.out.println(b);
```

### Output

```text
25
```

---

## char → int (ASCII Value)

```java
char ch = 'A';
int x = ch;

System.out.println(x);
```

### Output

```text
65
```

---

## int → char

```java
int x = 65;
char ch = (char) x;

System.out.println(ch);
```

### Output

```text
A
```

